{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01L8E9ceiRTfh1qNi581nor1","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Pack 6.G handoff — Canonical-SQLite tuning on the F.0 baseline\n2\t\n3\tPhase 9 Pack 6.G continues AC-020 closure work after Pack 6 closed\n4\tF.0 (thread-affine reader workers KEPT, human override of REVERT\n5\trule) on 2026-05-04. Pack 6.G stays inside canonical/release SQLite\n6\t— no WAL2, no `libsqlite3-sys` swap, no rusqlite replacement. Those\n7\tremain Pack 7+ research territory.\n8\t\n9\tF.0 removed Rust-side ReaderPool / cross-thread-handoff cost\n10\t(speedup 1.49×→3.49×, +2.34×). The residual gap is now plausibly\n11\tSQLite-internal: WAL shared-memory atomics, checkpoint pressure,\n12\tper-connection allocator (lookaside), and / or parse cost on\n13\tsticky long-lived reader connections. Pack 6.G attacks each of\n14\tthose with the smallest-radius, highest-evidence canonical-SQLite\n15\tlevers, in the order the telemetry pass picks.\n16\t\n17\t## 1. Read order on resume\n18\t\n19\t1. `dev/plan/runs/STATUS.md` — Pack 6 closed state + Pack 6.G\n20\t   active phase.\n21\t2. `dev/plan/runs/F0-thread-affine-readers-output.json` — F.0\n22\t   numeric baseline + worker pool topology summary.\n23\t3. `dev/plan/runs/F0-review-20260504T122055Z.md` — codex BLOCK\n24\t   findings + override rationale; key for future spawn discipline.\n25\t4. `dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` §4 (kept) + §5\n26\t   (do-not-retry) + §11 (Pack 5 narrative). §5 still binds — no\n27\t   retry of B.1 / C.1 / E.1 without explicit override.\n28\t5. `dev/plan/prompts/01-orchestrator-resume.md` §4 — anti-chaining\n29\t   defenses (PREAMBLE + `--disallowedTools Task Agent` + stream-\n30\t   json). Apply on every spawn.\n31\t6. The next phase prompt per \"Next action\" in STATUS.md.\n32\t\n33\t## 2. State at this hand-off\n34\t\n35\t- Branch: `0.6.0-rewrite`. Tip: `a00cd13` at handoff creation.\n36\t- F.0 commits already on tip: `4ebdd68` (refactor) + `29cdc6f`\n37\t  (cfg-gate fix) + `a00cd13` (KEEP bookkeeping).\n38\t- AC-020 N=5 numbers (post-F.0, this host): seq 531 ms / conc\n39\t  155 ms / speedup 3.49×. Required ≥ 5.0× KEEP / ≤ 80 ms conc.\n40\t  Gap: 75 ms above conc bound; 1.51× below speedup floor.\n41\t- Host caveat: this worktree machine runs ~3× slower in absolute\n42\t  ms than the Pack 5 reference machine. Cross-pack comparisons\n43\t  use the speedup ratio, not absolute ms.\n44\t- AC-017, AC-018 green; AC-018 drain 56 ms.\n45\t- Active worktrees: none.\n46\t- Anti-chaining defenses verified WORKING on F.0 spawn (single\n47\t  coherent agent; no Task spawns). Keep on for all G-phase spawns.\n48\t\n49\t## 3. Pack 5 / Pack 6 falsifications you do not retry\n50\t\n51\tPer the whitepaper §5 do-not-retry list:\n52\t\n53\t- Runtime `sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD)` (B.1).\n54\t- Compile-time `SQLITE_THREADSAFE=2` rebuild (C.1).\n55\t- Read-path `prepare_cached` on borrow/release pool connections\n56\t  (E.1). **Note:** G.2 in this packet revisits `prepare_cached` on\n57\t  the F.0 _thread-affine_ connections, which is a different\n58\t  topology and a different argument. Treat G.2 as new territory,\n59\t  not an §5 retry — see G.2 prompt for the explicit override\n60\t  rationale.\n61\t- Reader `cache_size` / `mmap_size` global tuning (Pack 5 reverted\n62\t  experiment ledger). G.0 may _measure_ mmap_size effects but does\n63\t  not change the production default.\n64\t- Reader open flags `READ_ONLY | NO_MUTEX`. G-phase keeps\n65\t  serialized open flags; thread-affine ownership is the safety\n66\t  argument, not the open-flag bits.\n67\t\n68\t## 4. Authorized G-phase interventions (in execution order)\n69\t\n70\t### G.0 — WAL / checkpoint telemetry pass (read-only)\n71\t\n72\tRe-capture AC-020 perf evidence on the F.0 tip with extended\n73\tsymbol grouping. Distinguish:\n74\t\n75\t- WAL shared-memory atomics (`walIndexMap`, `walFrames`, `walRead*`\n76\t  function family, atomic / CAS primitives inside `pager.c` / `wal.c`).\n77\t- Checkpoint cost (`sqlite3WalCheckpoint`, busy-handler interaction,\n78\t  auto-checkpoint threshold hits).\n79\t- Per-connection allocator behavior (`sqlite3MallocSize`,\n80\t  `sqlite3_release_memory`, lookaside hit/miss if surfaceable).\n81\t- Parse cost on sticky reader connections (`sqlite3RunParser`,\n82\t  `sqlite3VdbePrepare`). Should be high if E.1 hypothesis applies\n83\t  to F.0 topology; should be low if F.0 already amortized it.\n84\t- Our code share (engine + worker dispatch).\n85\t\n86\tOutput: classification JSON + a short reviewer-ready note picking\n87\tthe strongest single lever among G.1 / G.2 / G.3 for the next\n88\tphase. No production code change. No commit unless the diagnostic\n89\tadds a `#[ignore]`-gated counter test.\n90\t\n91\t### G.1 — Reader-worker lookaside tuning\n92\t\n93\tConfigure SQLite per-connection lookaside immediately after\n94\t`Connection::open` for each F.0 reader worker. Use\n95\t`sqlite3_db_config(SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE, ...)` with\n96\tdocumented sane defaults (per https://www.sqlite.org/malloc.html\n97\t§3 — typical 1200-byte slots, 100 slots, sized for the workload's\n98\tprepared-statement footprint; revise from G.0 evidence).\n99\t\n100\tExpected impact (per SQLite docs): ~10–15% overall perf in\n101\tallocator-heavy workloads. Reader-side, expressed across N=8\n102\tworkers with sticky connections, is exactly the documented happy\n103\tpath. Sequential effect: small. Concurrent effect: small-to-\n104\tmedium if the allocator is contended.\n105\t\n106\tKEEP / REVERT decision rule lives in `G1-reader-lookaside.md`.\n107\tNumeric KEEP target: any clean, reproducible improvement on\n108\tconcurrent_median_ms with no AC-017 / AC-018 regression. Lookaside\n109\tis too small a lever to require AC-020 closure alone — it is a\n110\tsequencing decision, not a closer.\n111\t\n112\t### G.2 — Per-worker prepared-statement cache (sticky-connection revisit of E.1)\n113\t\n114\tE.1 (Pack 5) added `prepare_cached` on the four read-path search\n115\tstatements against borrow/release pool connections. Sequential\n116\timproved -13.7%, concurrent unchanged, ratio worsened, codex BLOCK\n117\ton public surface + decision-rule mismatch + partial test. REVERTED.\n118\t\n119\tThe F.0 topology _is_ the natural shape for prepared-statement\n120\tcaching: each reader worker owns one connection for its lifetime,\n121\tso the cache amortizes across the worker's full lifetime, not just\n122\tthe brief borrow window. G.2 re-runs that experiment with two\n123\tbinding constraints from E.1's review:\n124\t\n125\t- All four statements covered (no partial test).\n126\t- No public Rust API expansion. Use private worker-internal cache\n127\t  with an integration test that drives observable behavior, not a\n128\t  `pub fn ..._for_test` accessor unless it is `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]`-gated and explicitly justified in the diff.\n129\t\n130\tKEEP target: AC-020 numerics improve cleanly (no ratio worsening).\n131\tThe Pack 5 §5 entry binds: G.2 is not a retry of the same\n132\texperiment; it is the same SQL change applied to a strictly\n133\tdifferent connection-lifetime topology. Whitepaper §12 carries the\n134\texplicit override note.\n135\t\n136\t### G.3 — WAL checkpoint policy / tuning\n137\t\n138\tAdjust auto-checkpoint threshold (PRAGMA `wal_autocheckpoint`),\n139\tbusy timeout, or move to an explicit application-driven checkpoint\n140\tschedule on the writer side. If G.0 telemetry says checkpoint cost\n141\tis small or zero on the read-heavy fixture, G.3 may be SKIPPED in\n142\tthis packet and queued for a real-write-load packet.\n143\t\n144\tKEEP target: lower variance + lower max latency on AC-020\n145\tconcurrent runs without regressing AC-017 / AC-018.\n146\t\n147\t## 5. Phase ordering\n148\t\n149\t1. G.0 telemetry first. Picks strongest lever or surfaces a non-\n150\t   listed bottleneck (orchestrator pivot point).\n151\t2. Run interventions in the order G.0 picks. Default order is\n152\t   G.1 → G.2 → G.3.\n153\t3. After each intervention: KEEP or REVERT, then re-measure\n154\t   AC-020 N=5 and update the chained baseline-of-record.\n155\t4. Final synthesis at packet close: cumulative speedup vs F.0\n156\t   baseline (3.49×) and vs the original Pack 5 baseline (1.49×).\n157\t\n158\t## 6. Decision rules (per phase)\n159\t\n160\t- KEEP iff AC-017 + AC-018 stay green AND AC-020 numerics improve\n161\t  cleanly (no ratio worsening, no concurrent_median_ms regression\n162\t  outside one stddev) AND no contract / public-surface violation.\n163\t- INCONCLUSIVE iff numerics flat within noise; record evidence and\n164\t  move on.\n165\t- REVERT iff any of the above fails.\n166\t\n167\tThe packet-close success definition is **not** \"AC-020 closes\n168\twithin 0.6.0\". It is \"every canonical-SQLite lever has been tried,\n169\tKEEPs are landed, and the residual gap is documented well enough\n170\tthat Pack 7 (WAL2 / vendor-SQLite / reader-writer split) can be\n171\tscoped from evidence rather than guess.\"\n172\t\n173\t## 7. Reviewer requirements\n174\t\n175\tCodex `gpt-5.4` high reviewer **mandatory on KEEP / INCONCLUSIVE**\n176\tfor G.1 / G.2 / G.3. G.0 is read-only diagnostics — reviewer\n177\toptional unless it lands a counter test.\n178\t\n179\tReviewer must confirm per phase:\n180\t\n181\t- No retry of an §5 do-not-retry experiment without explicit\n182\t  override note in the prompt + whitepaper.\n183\t- No public Rust API expansion without ADR / interface-doc work,\n184\t  or `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]` gating with the existing convention.\n185\t- AC-018 unchanged; same-snapshot cursor contract (REQ-013 /\n186\t  AC-059b / REQ-055) preserved.\n187\t- `./scripts/agent-verify.sh` run after meaningful edits (not\n188\t  `dev/agent-verify.sh` — that path does not exist, F.0 reviewer\n189\t  block #3).\n190\t\n191\t## 8. Out of scope for Pack 6.G\n192\t\n193\t- WAL2 mode. Branch-only SQLite; Pack 7 territory.\n194\t- `libsqlite3-sys` replacement / vendor-SQLite path. Pack 7.\n195\t- Reader/writer physical separation. Pack 7.\n196\t- Schema/index changes (e.g. `canonical_nodes(write_cursor)`).\n197\t- Any change that re-opens borrow/release pooling. F.0 is the\n198\t  load-bearing topology for the entire G-phase.\n199\t- Public Rust API expansion. `_for_test` accessors only with\n200\t  `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]` per F.0 reviewer convention.\n201\t\n202\t## 9. Failure interpretation\n203\t\n204\tIf G.0 + G.1 + G.2 + G.3 all land KEEP and AC-020 still does not\n205\tclose: ship 0.6.0 with REQ-020 deferred (per the F.0 packet-close\n206\tposition) and open Pack 7 with the cumulative G-phase evidence as\n207\tthe input.\n208\t\n209\tIf telemetry instead surfaces a **new** bottleneck class (e.g. a\n210\tspecific hot path in `vec0` that is amenable to a SQL or query-\n211\tplan tweak), the orchestrator may add a G.4 phase by appending to\n212\tthis handoff and the STATUS phase-results table — same review +\n213\tTDD discipline applies.\n214\t\n215\t## 10. Spawning interventions\n216\t\n217\tUse the resume §4 spawn block with anti-chaining defenses. Per-\n218\tphase prompts live alongside this handoff:\n219\t\n220\t- `dev/plan/prompts/G0-wal-checkpoint-telemetry.md`\n221\t- `dev/plan/prompts/G1-reader-lookaside.md` (authored after G.0)\n222\t- `dev/plan/prompts/G2-per-worker-stmt-cache.md` (authored after\n223\t  G.0 / G.1 KEEP)\n224\t- `dev/plan/prompts/G3-checkpoint-tuning.md` (authored after\n225\t  G.0 / G.1 / G.2)\n226\t\n227\tImplementer model: Opus 4.7 high. Reviewer: codex `gpt-5.4` high.\n228\tWorktree pattern: `/tmp/fdb-pack6G-<phase>-<ts>`. Branch:\n229\t`pack6G-<phase>-<ts>`.\n230\t\n231\t## 11. Pause points\n232\t\n233\t- After G.0 returns. Orchestrator reviews telemetry JSON, picks\n234\t  next-phase ordering, and pauses for human review before\n235\t  spawning G.1.\n236\t- After each KEEP / REVERT decision (§3 update protocol in\n237\t  `01-orchestrator-resume.md`).\n238\t- After packet close (cumulative-vs-F.0 + cumulative-vs-Pack-5\n239\t  numbers in the final synthesis JSON).\n240\t\n241\t## Update log\n242\t\n243\t- 2026-05-04 — Authored from the user's \"Best next opportunities\n244\t  on top of F.0\" briefing. G.0 telemetry first; default ordering\n245\t  G.1 → G.2 → G.3; Pack 6 F.0 baseline `a00cd13` (seq 531 ms /\n246\t  conc 155 ms / speedup 3.49× / N=5).\n247\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"68ae7ac2-a6c4-47f9-8330-cc3345895982","uuid":"359f72a7-86f0-4a5f-8641-e36d62345578","timestamp":"2026-05-04T13:29:04.918Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/fdb-pack6G-G0-20260504T132839Z/dev/plan/prompts/04-pack6G-handoff-canonical-sqlite-tuning.md","content":"# Pack 6.G handoff — Canonical-SQLite tuning on the F.0 baseline\n\nPhase 9 Pack 6.G continues AC-020 closure work after Pack 6 closed\nF.0 (thread-affine reader workers KEPT, human override of REVERT\nrule) on 2026-05-04. Pack 6.G stays inside canonical/release SQLite\n— no WAL2, no `libsqlite3-sys` swap, no rusqlite replacement. Those\nremain Pack 7+ research territory.\n\nF.0 removed Rust-side ReaderPool / cross-thread-handoff cost\n(speedup 1.49×→3.49×, +2.34×). The residual gap is now plausibly\nSQLite-internal: WAL shared-memory atomics, checkpoint pressure,\nper-connection allocator (lookaside), and / or parse cost on\nsticky long-lived reader connections. Pack 6.G attacks each of\nthose with the smallest-radius, highest-evidence canonical-SQLite\nlevers, in the order the telemetry pass picks.\n\n## 1. Read order on resume\n\n1. `dev/plan/runs/STATUS.md` — Pack 6 closed state + Pack 6.G\n   active phase.\n2. `dev/plan/runs/F0-thread-affine-readers-output.json` — F.0\n   numeric baseline + worker pool topology summary.\n3. `dev/plan/runs/F0-review-20260504T122055Z.md` — codex BLOCK\n   findings + override rationale; key for future spawn discipline.\n4. `dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` §4 (kept) + §5\n   (do-not-retry) + §11 (Pack 5 narrative). §5 still binds — no\n   retry of B.1 / C.1 / E.1 without explicit override.\n5. `dev/plan/prompts/01-orchestrator-resume.md` §4 — anti-chaining\n   defenses (PREAMBLE + `--disallowedTools Task Agent` + stream-\n   json). Apply on every spawn.\n6. The next phase prompt per \"Next action\" in STATUS.md.\n\n## 2. State at this hand-off\n\n- Branch: `0.6.0-rewrite`. Tip: `a00cd13` at handoff creation.\n- F.0 commits already on tip: `4ebdd68` (refactor) + `29cdc6f`\n  (cfg-gate fix) + `a00cd13` (KEEP bookkeeping).\n- AC-020 N=5 numbers (post-F.0, this host): seq 531 ms / conc\n  155 ms / speedup 3.49×. Required ≥ 5.0× KEEP / ≤ 80 ms conc.\n  Gap: 75 ms above conc bound; 1.51× below speedup floor.\n- Host caveat: this worktree machine runs ~3× slower in absolute\n  ms than the Pack 5 reference machine. Cross-pack comparisons\n  use the speedup ratio, not absolute ms.\n- AC-017, AC-018 green; AC-018 drain 56 ms.\n- Active worktrees: none.\n- Anti-chaining defenses verified WORKING on F.0 spawn (single\n  coherent agent; no Task spawns). Keep on for all G-phase spawns.\n\n## 3. Pack 5 / Pack 6 falsifications you do not retry\n\nPer the whitepaper §5 do-not-retry list:\n\n- Runtime `sqlite3_config(SQLITE_CONFIG_MULTITHREAD)` (B.1).\n- Compile-time `SQLITE_THREADSAFE=2` rebuild (C.1).\n- Read-path `prepare_cached` on borrow/release pool connections\n  (E.1). **Note:** G.2 in this packet revisits `prepare_cached` on\n  the F.0 _thread-affine_ connections, which is a different\n  topology and a different argument. Treat G.2 as new territory,\n  not an §5 retry — see G.2 prompt for the explicit override\n  rationale.\n- Reader `cache_size` / `mmap_size` global tuning (Pack 5 reverted\n  experiment ledger). G.0 may _measure_ mmap_size effects but does\n  not change the production default.\n- Reader open flags `READ_ONLY | NO_MUTEX`. G-phase keeps\n  serialized open flags; thread-affine ownership is the safety\n  argument, not the open-flag bits.\n\n## 4. Authorized G-phase interventions (in execution order)\n\n### G.0 — WAL / checkpoint telemetry pass (read-only)\n\nRe-capture AC-020 perf evidence on the F.0 tip with extended\nsymbol grouping. Distinguish:\n\n- WAL shared-memory atomics (`walIndexMap`, `walFrames`, `walRead*`\n  function family, atomic / CAS primitives inside `pager.c` / `wal.c`).\n- Checkpoint cost (`sqlite3WalCheckpoint`, busy-handler interaction,\n  auto-checkpoint threshold hits).\n- Per-connection allocator behavior (`sqlite3MallocSize`,\n  `sqlite3_release_memory`, lookaside hit/miss if surfaceable).\n- Parse cost on sticky reader connections (`sqlite3RunParser`,\n  `sqlite3VdbePrepare`). Should be high if E.1 hypothesis applies\n  to F.0 topology; should be low if F.0 already amortized it.\n- Our code share (engine + worker dispatch).\n\nOutput: classification JSON + a short reviewer-ready note picking\nthe strongest single lever among G.1 / G.2 / G.3 for the next\nphase. No production code change. No commit unless the diagnostic\nadds a `#[ignore]`-gated counter test.\n\n### G.1 — Reader-worker lookaside tuning\n\nConfigure SQLite per-connection lookaside immediately after\n`Connection::open` for each F.0 reader worker. Use\n`sqlite3_db_config(SQLITE_DBCONFIG_LOOKASIDE, ...)` with\ndocumented sane defaults (per https://www.sqlite.org/malloc.html\n§3 — typical 1200-byte slots, 100 slots, sized for the workload's\nprepared-statement footprint; revise from G.0 evidence).\n\nExpected impact (per SQLite docs): ~10–15% overall perf in\nallocator-heavy workloads. Reader-side, expressed across N=8\nworkers with sticky connections, is exactly the documented happy\npath. Sequential effect: small. Concurrent effect: small-to-\nmedium if the allocator is contended.\n\nKEEP / REVERT decision rule lives in `G1-reader-lookaside.md`.\nNumeric KEEP target: any clean, reproducible improvement on\nconcurrent_median_ms with no AC-017 / AC-018 regression. Lookaside\nis too small a lever to require AC-020 closure alone — it is a\nsequencing decision, not a closer.\n\n### G.2 — Per-worker prepared-statement cache (sticky-connection revisit of E.1)\n\nE.1 (Pack 5) added `prepare_cached` on the four read-path search\nstatements against borrow/release pool connections. Sequential\nimproved -13.7%, concurrent unchanged, ratio worsened, codex BLOCK\non public surface + decision-rule mismatch + partial test. REVERTED.\n\nThe F.0 topology _is_ the natural shape for prepared-statement\ncaching: each reader worker owns one connection for its lifetime,\nso the cache amortizes across the worker's full lifetime, not just\nthe brief borrow window. G.2 re-runs that experiment with two\nbinding constraints from E.1's review:\n\n- All four statements covered (no partial test).\n- No public Rust API expansion. Use private worker-internal cache\n  with an integration test that drives observable behavior, not a\n  `pub fn ..._for_test` accessor unless it is `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]`-gated and explicitly justified in the diff.\n\nKEEP target: AC-020 numerics improve cleanly (no ratio worsening).\nThe Pack 5 §5 entry binds: G.2 is not a retry of the same\nexperiment; it is the same SQL change applied to a strictly\ndifferent connection-lifetime topology. Whitepaper §12 carries the\nexplicit override note.\n\n### G.3 — WAL checkpoint policy / tuning\n\nAdjust auto-checkpoint threshold (PRAGMA `wal_autocheckpoint`),\nbusy timeout, or move to an explicit application-driven checkpoint\nschedule on the writer side. If G.0 telemetry says checkpoint cost\nis small or zero on the read-heavy fixture, G.3 may be SKIPPED in\nthis packet and queued for a real-write-load packet.\n\nKEEP target: lower variance + lower max latency on AC-020\nconcurrent runs without regressing AC-017 / AC-018.\n\n## 5. Phase ordering\n\n1. G.0 telemetry first. Picks strongest lever or surfaces a non-\n   listed bottleneck (orchestrator pivot point).\n2. Run interventions in the order G.0 picks. Default order is\n   G.1 → G.2 → G.3.\n3. After each intervention: KEEP or REVERT, then re-measure\n   AC-020 N=5 and update the chained baseline-of-record.\n4. Final synthesis at packet close: cumulative speedup vs F.0\n   baseline (3.49×) and vs the original Pack 5 baseline (1.49×).\n\n## 6. Decision rules (per phase)\n\n- KEEP iff AC-017 + AC-018 stay green AND AC-020 numerics improve\n  cleanly (no ratio worsening, no concurrent_median_ms regression\n  outside one stddev) AND no contract / public-surface violation.\n- INCONCLUSIVE iff numerics flat within noise; record evidence and\n  move on.\n- REVERT iff any of the above fails.\n\nThe packet-close success definition is **not** \"AC-020 closes\nwithin 0.6.0\". It is \"every canonical-SQLite lever has been tried,\nKEEPs are landed, and the residual gap is documented well enough\nthat Pack 7 (WAL2 / vendor-SQLite / reader-writer split) can be\nscoped from evidence rather than guess.\"\n\n## 7. Reviewer requirements\n\nCodex `gpt-5.4` high reviewer **mandatory on KEEP / INCONCLUSIVE**\nfor G.1 / G.2 / G.3. G.0 is read-only diagnostics — reviewer\noptional unless it lands a counter test.\n\nReviewer must confirm per phase:\n\n- No retry of an §5 do-not-retry experiment without explicit\n  override note in the prompt + whitepaper.\n- No public Rust API expansion without ADR / interface-doc work,\n  or `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]` gating with the existing convention.\n- AC-018 unchanged; same-snapshot cursor contract (REQ-013 /\n  AC-059b / REQ-055) preserved.\n- `./scripts/agent-verify.sh` run after meaningful edits (not\n  `dev/agent-verify.sh` — that path does not exist, F.0 reviewer\n  block #3).\n\n## 8. Out of scope for Pack 6.G\n\n- WAL2 mode. Branch-only SQLite; Pack 7 territory.\n- `libsqlite3-sys` replacement / vendor-SQLite path. Pack 7.\n- Reader/writer physical separation. Pack 7.\n- Schema/index changes (e.g. `canonical_nodes(write_cursor)`).\n- Any change that re-opens borrow/release pooling. F.0 is the\n  load-bearing topology for the entire G-phase.\n- Public Rust API expansion. `_for_test` accessors only with\n  `#[cfg(debug_assertions)]` per F.0 reviewer convention.\n\n## 9. Failure interpretation\n\nIf G.0 + G.1 + G.2 + G.3 all land KEEP and AC-020 still does not\nclose: ship 0.6.0 with REQ-020 deferred (per the F.0 packet-close\nposition) and open Pack 7 with the cumulative G-phase evidence as\nthe input.\n\nIf telemetry instead surfaces a **new** bottleneck class (e.g. a\nspecific hot path in `vec0` that is amenable to a SQL or query-\nplan tweak), the orchestrator may add a G.4 phase by appending to\nthis handoff and the STATUS phase-results table — same review +\nTDD discipline applies.\n\n## 10. Spawning interventions\n\nUse the resume §4 spawn block with anti-chaining defenses. Per-\nphase prompts live alongside this handoff:\n\n- `dev/plan/prompts/G0-wal-checkpoint-telemetry.md`\n- `dev/plan/prompts/G1-reader-lookaside.md` (authored after G.0)\n- `dev/plan/prompts/G2-per-worker-stmt-cache.md` (authored after\n  G.0 / G.1 KEEP)\n- `dev/plan/prompts/G3-checkpoint-tuning.md` (authored after\n  G.0 / G.1 / G.2)\n\nImplementer model: Opus 4.7 high. Reviewer: codex `gpt-5.4` high.\nWorktree pattern: `/tmp/fdb-pack6G-<phase>-<ts>`. Branch:\n`pack6G-<phase>-<ts>`.\n\n## 11. Pause points\n\n- After G.0 returns. Orchestrator reviews telemetry JSON, picks\n  next-phase ordering, and pauses for human review before\n  spawning G.1.\n- After each KEEP / REVERT decision (§3 update protocol in\n  `01-orchestrator-resume.md`).\n- After packet close (cumulative-vs-F.0 + cumulative-vs-Pack-5\n  numbers in the final synthesis JSON).\n\n## Update log\n\n- 2026-05-04 — Authored from the user's \"Best next opportunities\n  on top of F.0\" briefing. G.0 telemetry first; default ordering\n  G.1 → G.2 → G.3; Pack 6 F.0 baseline `a00cd13` (seq 531 ms /\n  conc 155 ms / speedup 3.49× / N=5).\n","numLines":247,"startLine":1,"totalLines":247}}}
